The Aeneid is conventionally spoken of as Virgil's greatest work, and, possibly, the dramatis power of the fourth Book and the ima- ginative grandeur of the sixth surpass anything in the Georgics, but as a monument of his literary skill they stand unequassedss

The Aeneid consists of twelvebooks, and is an epic poem professedly modelled on Homer.⁴ The first six books describe the wanderings and the second six the wars of Aeneas, so that the whole work constitutes a Roman Odyssey and Iliad in one.
